  "prompt": "What is iTunes?",
  "response": "iTunes is a media player, media library, Internet radio broadcaster, and mobile device management application developed by Apple Inc. It was originally released in January 2001 and was primarily used to play, download, and organize digital music and video files on personal computers running the macOS and Windows operating systems. iTunes also served as the primary software for syncing content with iPods, iPhones, and iPads prior to the introduction of standalone apps and services integrated into macOS, iOS, and other Apple platforms.\n\nBesides its functionality as a media player and library, iTunes provided access to the iTunes Store, where users could purchase and download music, movies, TV shows, podcasts, audiobooks, and apps. Over time, other Apple services and apps have evolved to take over many of the roles that iTunes used to fulfill. For example, the Apple Music app now handles music streaming and library management, while Apple Podcasts and Apple TV apps handle podcasts and video content, respectively.\n\nAs of macOS Catalina (released in October 2019), the functionalities of iTunes have been split into separate apps: Music, Apple TV, and Podcasts, with syncing and device management now handled by Finder on Mac computers. While iTunes remains available on Windows, its role has gradually diminished as Apple's ecosystem has evolved.",
